GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 2
HOUSE BILL 515
Committee Substitute Favorable 4/29/25
Short Title: North Carolina Economic Abuse Prevention Act. (Public)
Sponsors:
Referred to:
March 26, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO ENACT THE NORTH CAROLINA ECONOMIC ABUSE PREVENTION ACT.
3 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
4 SECTION 1.(a) The General Assembly finds that survivors of domestic violence
5 and the children of domestic violence survivors undergo multiple forms of abuses, including
6 monetary abuse, and that survivors of domestic violence need multiple pathways to remedy
7 coerced debt and to repair credit reports. Therefore, it is the public policy of this State to provide
8 remedies for economic abuse against domestic violence survivors.
9 SECTION 1.(b) The General Statutes are amended by adding a new Chapter to read:
10 "Chapter 1H.
11 "Economic Abuse Prevention Act.
12 "§ 1H-1. Short title.
13 This Chapter shall be known and may be cited as the North Carolina Economic Abuse
14 Prevention Act.
15 "§ 1H-2. Definitions.
16 The following definitions apply to this Chapter:
17 (1) Abuse. – As defined in G.S. 50C-1(1).
18 (2) Adequate documentation. – Documentation that identifies a particular debt, or
19 portion thereof, as coerced debt, describes the circumstances under which the
20 coerced debt was incurred, and takes the form of any of the following:
21 a. A police report indicating the debtor was a victim of domestic violence
22 or elder abuse.
23 b. A Federal Trade Commission identity theft report indicating that the
24 debtor has been the victim of identity theft that identifies a particular
25 debt, or portion thereof, as coerced, but not as identity theft.
26 c. A court order issued under Chapter 50 or Chapter 50B of the General
27 Statutes stating that the debtor incurred debts as a result of abusive
28 coercion from any of the following:
29 1. A current or former spouse.
30 2. An individual with whom the debtor has a child in common.
31 3. An individual with whom the debtor is or was in a dating
32 relationship.
33 4. A current or former resident of the debtor's household.
34 d. A sworn written certification from a qualified third-party professional
35 based on information they received while acting in a professional
36 capacity. This documentation shall be signed by a qualified third-party
*H515-v-2*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 professional and display the letterhead, address, and telephone number
2 of the office, institution, center, or organization, as appropriate, that
3 engages or employs, whether financially compensated or not, the
4 qualified third-party professional, or, if the qualified third-party
5 professional is self-employed, the documentation shall display the
6 letterhead, address, and telephone number of the qualified third-party
7 professional.
8 (3) Claim. – A right to payment for any debt, excluding secured debt, whether or
9 not that right is liquidated, unliquidated, fixed, contingent, matured,
10 unmatured, disputed, undisputed, legal, or equitable.
11 (4) Claimant. – A person or an entity who has or purports to have a claim against
12 a debtor arising from coerced debt, or that person's or entity's successor or
13 assignee. This definition includes a debt collector or a debt buyer. The term
14 does not include a person who caused the claim described in subdivision (3)
15 of this section to arise through duress, intimidation, threat of force, force,
16 fraud, or undue influence perpetrated against the debtor.
17 (5) Coerced debt. – A particular debt, or portion thereof, for personal, family, or
18 household use in the name of a debtor who is a victim of domestic violence as
19 defined in G.S. 50B-1, or a victim of domestic abuse as defined in
20 G.S. 14-32.3(a), or a current or former child in foster care as defined in
21 G.S. 131D-10.2, incurred as a result of duress, intimidation, threat of force,
22 force, or undue influence.
23 (6) Debtor. – A person who owes or is otherwise liable for coerced debt.
24 (7) Fraud. – An initial fraudulent act that is perpetrated against the debtor.
25 (8) Immediate family member. – As defined in G.S. 53-244.030(13).
26 (9) Person. – A natural person.
27 (10) Qualified third-party professional. – Any of the following who also has a
28 degree, certificate, or license from an accredited program for counseling
29 domestic violence victims:
30 a. Any agent of a domestic violence or sexual assault program, as defined
31 in G.S. 8-53.12.
32 b. A board-certified psychiatrist or psychologist.
33 c. A licensed marriage and family therapist.
34 d. A licensed professional clinical counselor.
35 e. A clinical social worker or a domestic violence professional.
36 f. A social worker or caseworker employed by a county department of
37 social services for the purposes described in G.S. 108A-100 or
38 G.S. 7B-100.
39 g. A noncredentialed domestic violence worker.
40 (11) Secured debt. – An obligation for which the payment or performance of is
41 secured by a security interest in real or personal property. Any actions for
42 collection to obtain a final judgment, an order for possession of collateral
43 securing the debt, or to collect any deficiency balance owing after the
44 liquidation of collateral pledged to secure the debt are included in this
45 definition.
46 (12) Sworn written certification. – A document in which the author declares under
47 penalty of perjury as true any material fact, and which is accompanied by the
48 following, to the extent that an item listed below is relevant to the debtor's
49 allegation that the debt is coerced debt:
50 a. A copy of the debtor's drivers license or identification card, as issued
51 by the State.
